Why does Spark even exist? Picture two hundred gigabytes of data and a laptop with sixteen gigs of RAM. Load it in pandas and it crashes on the very first line.

So you get clever — you split the file into chunks and loop over them. But now you own a distributed system: you're tracking which chunks finished, which ones failed, and how to group-by across all of them at once. That's a second job, and it's a hard one.

That's the problem Spark solves. Spark is a distributed compute engine. You write your code as if you have one giant table — no chunking, no bookkeeping. Under the hood, Spark slices that table into partitions, hands each one to a machine, runs your code on all of them in parallel, and gathers the results back.

And the shift from pandas is the whole point. pandas is one process, running immediately, on memory it owns. Spark is a plan you describe, scheduled across many machines, with the data moved for you. Every idea later in the course builds on that one distinction.

